    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-07-21T06:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-07-21T06:30:00-05:00" n="114"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d114">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/60: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Harbin</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hanson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Harbin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-07-21T20:00:00+08:30"
                            >July 21, 1929—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 22—12:32 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Report received to the effect that two Chinese merchant ships <hi rend="italic"
                        >Ilan</hi> [and] <hi rend="italic">Haicheng</hi> seized by Soviet Russians
                    on Amur River who have assured Roy Talbot, American Commissioner of Customs,
                    Taheiho, that they will treat kindly his wife and child who are on <hi
                        rend="italic">Ilan</hi>. No new developments except all Soviet Russian
                    employees of the railway have been requested to resign their positions by order
                    of the Soviet Government. Legation informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hanson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
